        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="italic">18, Fenchurch Street, | London, | E. C</hi> .</placeName>
                    <date>19<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. March 1878</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I have received your note of yesterday containing instructions for a second codicil to your will,—also your will &amp; the first codicil.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> The scheme of your will is that out of your estate £12000 is to be raised for each of your children—sons and daughters and I think it may be convenient that this scheme should be adhered to, by the intended codicil providing that £14000, instead of £12000, shall be raised for each child;—the ultimate residue being given equally amongst the sons.— If this should not be in accordance with your wishes perhaps you will be so good as to let me hear from you.</p>
<p>I am | My dear Sir | Yours very truly | W<hi rend="superscript">m</hi>. M Hacon <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">Charles R. Darwin Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi>. | Down | Beckenham | Kent</p> 
                </div>
                
            </div>
            </div>
            
            
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">The letter to Hacon has not been found. CD had made a codicil to his will in 1871 (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 19, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7841.xml">letter from G. H. Darwin, [17 July 1871]</ref>). </note>
                
            </div> 
     
